To create a system to pick and select certain spells, you can modify the SpellsManager class to include user input that prompts them to select a spell by name or level. Here's an example:

```java
import java.util.Scanner;

public class SpellsManager {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Spell[] spells = new Spell[3];
        spells[0] = new Spell("Fireball", 50, 3);
        spells[1] = new Spell("Ice Storm", 30, 2);
        spells[2] = new Spell("Lightning Bolt", 70, 4);

        Scanner scanner = new Scanner(System.in);
        System.out.println("Enter the name or level of the spell you want to cast: ");
        String input = scanner.nextLine();
        System.out.println("Casting spell...");

        for (Spell spell : spells) {
            if (spell.getName().equalsIgnoreCase(input) || spell.getLevel() == Integer.parseInt(input)) {
                System.out.println("Name: " + spell.getName());
                System.out.println("Damage: " + spell.getDamage());
                System.out.println("Level: " + spell.getLevel());
                break;
            }
        }
    }
}

class Spell {
    private String name;
    private int damage;
    private int level;

    public Spell(String name, int damage, int level) {
        this.name = name;
        this.damage = damage;
        this.level = level;
    }

    public String getName() {
        return name;
    }

    public int getDamage() {
        return damage;
    }

    public int getLevel() {
        return level;
    }
}
```

